posts.title: Put out your cookies and get a good nights rest!
posts.content:
’Twas the night before Trump takes the White House, and all through D.C., The streets were a flutter, anticipation set free. The Capitol was lit, with flags hanging high, While pundits and critics let out a collective sigh.

The offices emptied, the halls fell quite still, As Washington prepared for the coming of will. The new President-elect, with his plans in his grasp, Was ready to lead, with a powerful gasp.

The White House, all quiet, in winter’s embrace, Waited for dawn to reveal a familiar face. The staff were all nestled, with caution and care, Dreaming of policies—what would he dare?

In Trump Tower, the mogul sat poised at his desk, Gazing at the future, which seemed quite grotesque. His campaign had been loud, filled with fire and flare, And now he was ready to take up the air.

With tax cuts and tariffs and walls to be built, He’d work to undo the years of the tilt. The country was restless, unsure what would come, Would it be unity or would the divide be undone?

The clock struck midnight, the time drawing near, For the moment when Trump would make all things clear. The swearing-in ceremony, the speeches, the cheers, A new chapter would start, erasing old fears.

On the streets below, in the glow of the night, Some cheered for the future, others feared the fight. But the nation stood ready, both anxious and proud, To welcome their leader, both quiet and loud.

Through the turmoil and noise, through all the debate, There was no denying this moment was great. For whether you loved him or feared his command, The night before Trump came, the country would stand.

And as dawn approached, with a golden sunrise, The world braced for the changes, unsure of the prize. For tomorrow would be a new era in view, The night before Trump, the world would renew.
